the present day. Using empirical data, such as capital offender and offense profiles, temporal and regional variations in capital punishment, and the impact of social media on public opinion and reform, contributors relay both the character of China's death penalty practices and the incremental changes that indicate reform. They then compare the Chinese experience to other countries throughout Asia and the world, showing how change can be implemented even within a non-democratic and rigid political system, but also the dangers of promoting policies that society may not be ready to embrace.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aCapital punishmentxChina. 0aCapital punishmentzChina. 0aCapital punishment. 0aCriminal justice, Administration ofxChina. 0aCriminal justice, Administration ofzChina. 7aLAW / Criminal Law / Sentencing.2bisacsh1 aChen, Xingliang, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFu, Hualing, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHood, Roger, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHood, Roger.1 aHu, Charlotte, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJiang, Shanhe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohnson, David T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLi, Yudu, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLiang, Bin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLiang, Bin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLu, Hong, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLu, Hong, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMiao, Michelle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTrevaskes, 